<br>
&quot;Every gram of structure must be trimmed, exotic materials and cutting-edge techniques are a necessity, and safety margins must be as slim as we dare if success is to be achieved.&quot;<br>
<br>
That quote says it all Mauk2 and the proposal you have made sounds like just the ticket we need to get back the heavy lift capacity we lost through NASA’s shortsightedness and paranoia. Actually the concept exceeds The SaturnV-D throw weight by a factor of 3 and would also be cheaper to build as far as airframe and structures are concerned.<br>
<br>
 The 7 chambered GCNR you propose would do its job in a very economical, safe, and spectacular fashion. I say it would be economical because when minimum weight criterion is applied to any vehicle be it a car or a rocket in order to squeeze every last bit of performance out of its power plant the cost of such a vehicle rises almost exponentially. With an Isp of 3000+ and high thrust to boot you have entered the BOILER PLATE ZONE. The technology and most of the cost is in the engines not spread around the vehicle in attempt to make up for a weak power plant.<br>
 <br>
I imagine a company with ship building experience would be a more logical choice for a contractor than a pure aerospace company. I would recommend General Dynamics since they have all the needed skills, tooling, and know how in place under one roof . The prime contractor should be The Electric Boat Division of General Dynamics. Los Alamos and their little brothers at Livermore should do the research and development on the power plant.<br>
<br>
I do however think that a Venture Star style lifting body rather than cylindrical stack should be considered. I think that a lifting body airframe would make atmospheric braking a bit easier and avoid that crazy maneuver of bringing the ship into a vertical position for landing.  Besides that it would be great to see that monster do a go around in a landing pattern frying chickens in the barnyard. <br>
<br>
With high ISP I imagine that the hull/ hydrogen tank could be made of .1875 inch thick Ats134 stain resistant steel or HY 100 steel backed by an aluminum honeycomb filled with an insulating material. The traditional stringer and rib internal bracing system would then ensure that you have a SHIP that would last for quite some time. <br>
The 1,000 ton payload could be additional fuel, life support supplies, and a reusable MEV (Mars Excursion Vehicle) if you wanted to take a quick jaunt to Mars along a high-energy transfer orbit. <br>
<br>
