<br>
&lt;sigh&gt;<br>
<br>
Ok, something bugged me about yales 80 gigawatt figure.  Even though yales has an annoying habit of not saying how he gets figures, he is also a smart cookie.  So I got to wondering where that figure came from, and so I did a little poking around, and I found out that yales was right!<br>
<br>
Oh dear.  <br>
<br>
What happened was this: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.gcse.com/energy/ke2.htm"> KE= 1/2m * v^2. </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> This is the kinetic energy formula, basic physics, which is basically kinetic energy equals one half the mass moving times the velocity squared.  <br>
<br>
It was the velocity squared thing which got me in my straight line comparisons.  You see, the exhaust velocity needed for an Isp of 3060 is WAY, WAY higher than that of chemical rockets, and the rules say, you have to square that.  So, squaring a larger number causes the energy needed to move a mass at that speed to go much higher than a straight line.<br>
<br>
So, let's do a little math.<br>
<br>
It is easy to calculate the mass flows of a rocket using this formula: wf = F / ISP.  Each thruster of the Liberty Ship ejects wf = 1,200,000 / 3060 = 392 pounds of hydrogen per second, or 177.85 kilos per second.<br>
<br>
There are seven thrusters, so that works out to 1245 kilos per second for the entire Liberty Ship.  <br>
<br>
To get an Isp of 3060, we have to have an exhaust stream speed of 30,000 meters per second.  That's how Isp works.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, using the kinetic energy formula, we can simply plug in the numbers: KE = (1/2 * 1245kg) * (30,000 m/sec)^2 .<br>
<br>
Or:   (1245 * 900,000,000) / 2<br>
<br>
Or:   560,250,000,000 joules.<br>
<br>
Since a watt is 1 joule per second, we get 560,250,000,000 watts.  Also known as 560 Gigawatts.<br>
<br>
Hmmmmm.<br>
<br>
Now, if this fact had been explained to me before I went out and did my research on silica transparency, I would have probably thrown up my hands and admitted defeat.<br>
<br>
80 Gigawatts per thruster is a LOT.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
However, as I posted above, I believe that technology has caught up to this problem.  Lets do a little more math.  <br>
<br>
As I calculated above, at a value of 30 gigawatts per thruster, the silica bulb with 10 square meters of surface area has to be cooled for 6 megawatts per square meter.  That figure seems quite solid to me.  (Unless somebody finds something else.)<br>
<br>
Now, if 30 gigawatts means 6 megawatts per square meter per centimeter of thickness, then 80 gigawatts means 16 megawatts per square meter per centimeter of thickness has to be removed from the bulb!<br>
<br>
A surprisingly tiny amount, all due to the incredible strides we have made in materials technology.  <br>
<br>
As I said before, ain't technology great?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, since the power levels are at the sky-high figures yales said they were at, I have to begin wondering how much uranium this design is going to burn up.  Plus, I think I am going to make the lightbulb larger, just to have more room to react more uranium!  <br>
<br>
Since I am lazy, I will increase the length to 4 meters, and will increase the diameter to 1.6 meters rather than 1 meter.<br>
<br>
This works out to a surface area for the bulb of 20 square meters instead of 10, so the new figure for the energy absorbed by the bulb is 8 megawatts per square meter per centimeter of thickness.  Almost exactly the same as before!  <br>
<br>
I always said that darn yales was a smart one....  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Anyway, I will be back after I have investigated how much uranium it will now take to fuel ths beast, and I will strive to answer folks questions at that time.  <br>
<br>
In the mean time, keep picking away!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
