 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 168<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/20/02 9:14:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=61>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Potential problems</span><hr size=1> You havn't answered my question. Yales actually made this point before.<br>
<br>
ALL reaction rockets must follow the inverse relationship between specific power (alpha, represented as @ here) and specific impulse (Isp). Specific power is kW/kg and specific impulse is Ns/kg. For example chemical propellants have high @ and low Isp. For the same mass an engine with a higher Isp will have a lower @. A NLB GCNR is a reaction rocket, so must follow this relationship. Thus your NLB would not have the high @ levels required for your calculations. You might be able to reach a T/W ratio of 1.3:1 (Considered possible for NLBs during the SEI studies), but 10:1 is beyond the capibilities of a NLB, or any form of GCNR for that matter. Thus you will need nearly 8 times as many engines as listed to achieve your origonanly thrust total. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/21/02 12:36:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Potential problems</span><hr size=1> Okay, did some quick and dirty calulations and feel much better now.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
According to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://physics.syr.edu/courses/modules/ENERGY/ENERGY_POLICY/tables.html"> this page </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> U235 contains 3.7 x 10e13 joules of energy per pound.  That is 37 trillion joules, or 37 trillion watts if it was all released in one second. <br>
<br>
(There is a reason why atomic bombs are fearsome!)<br>
<br>
Now, I just worked out (after yales poked me in the ribs about it) that the Liberty Ships thrusters need to generate 560 Gigawatts on the way to orbit.  We'll assume we run it at full power all the way up, for simplicity sake.  If we have to boost for 11 minutes to reach orbital insertion, then we have to expend 560 Gigawatts for 660 seconds.  Doing the math, we reach an energy expenditure of 369,600,000,000,000 or 3.696 x 10e14 joules.<br>
<br>
This means that almost exactly 10 pounds of U235 must fission on the trip up.  (YOWSA!)<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, if we use 20 percent enriched uranium, then 50 pounds of HEU 20 is needed to power the Liberty Ship on each trip.  However, 100 percent burnup seems a trifle ambitious, so lets assume we take ten times as much fissile material with us and only go for 10 percent burnup.  <br>
<br>
So, we have roughly 500 pounds of uranium onboard for power during the ascent phase.  (We'll need more to get back down again, but quite a bit less.)  Uranium Hexaflouride works out to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://web.ead.anl.gov/uranium/guide/ucompound/propertiesu/uranium.cfm"> two thirds </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> Uranium and one third flourine, so to get 500 pounds of Uranium, we need roughly 770 pounds of UF6, or about 350 kilos.<br>
<br>
So, each thruster gets 50 kilos of UF6 to burn on the way up.<br>
<br>
UF6 as a solid is nice and dense, 5.1 grams/cc.  So, all 50 kilos for each thruster can be stored in a nicely compact 10 liters of volume.  (Of course, we would use much more volume than that to take the fuel to deep non-criticality.)<br>
<br>
Compare this with the over 15,000 cubic METERS of liquid hydrogen tank.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Even with the huge power requirements, it is almost embarassing how little nuclear material the Liberty Ship uses to reach orbit.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
Now, as promised, questions answered!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
nebobgrenville: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> How are you getting all this extra thrust out of the engines? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
VOLUME, VOLUME, VOLUME!!!!!!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Ok, all joking aside, that is actually one of two methods that I envision that will allow the Liberty Ship thrusters to reach the power levels needed.  <br>
<br>
Let me explain my reasoning: <br>
<br>
There is a principal called the &quot;squared-cubed law.&quot;  It says basically that if the physical dimensions of an object are doubled (2x), the volume of the object goes up eight times (2x2x2) while the surface area of the object only increases 4 times (2x2).  This is easy to verify with the example of a 1 inch cube compared to a 2 inch cube compared to a 4 inch cube.<br>
<br>
A 1 inch cube has a surface area of 6 square inches, and a volume of 1 cubic inch.  <br>
<br>
A 2 inch cube has a surface area of 24 square inches (4 square inches on all six sides) and a volume of 8 cubic inches.<br>
<br>
A 4 inch cube has a surface area of 96 square inches and a volume of 64 cubic inches.<br>
<br>
See, the surface area increases 16 times, but the volume increases 64 times.<br>
<br>
Now in any GCNR, the area that must be kept cool is the SURFACE AREA of the inside of the thruster.  But, the WORKING VOLUME of the thruster is all the volume that can hold working fluid and be effectively coupled to the core.<br>
<br>
So, by the simple expedient of making the reaction chamber larger, we enclose more working volume, making it easier to get more thrust per pound of the structure of the thruster.  After all, the empty space enclosed by the GCNR doesn't weigh anything.  <br>
<br>
Of course, materials strengths lend a practical upper limit to how large you can make a thruster, but I suspect that with aluminum and composite construction, we can scale these well beyond 1.2million pounds of thrust.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, I also have another trick up my sleeve.  If you will recall, I said above that almost the entire internal structure of the Liberty Ship thruster will be perforated with <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.dfrc.nasa.gov/PAO/PAIS/HTML/FS-023-DFRC.html"> micropores, </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and small amounts of cold hydrogen/oxygen gas will be pumped through them while the thruster is operating.    (Note this is the opposite of the experimental plane I have linked, I mainly put up that link to show the micropores I envision.)<br>
<br>
This will serve to cool the fragile physical structures from the raging temperatures of the core, and equally as important, it will form a &quot;buffer&quot; of slow moving, cool gas that will protect the inside of the thruster from the very high speed hydrogen ions it is busily producing and throwing away.<br>
<br>
Indeed, the inside of the Liberty Ship thruster could be envisioned as being constructed of high pressure gases, which serve to contain and direct the furious power of the propellant.  The actual physical structures of the thruster are just there to support the gas layer, which is the true working surface.<br>
<br>
<br>
Basically, I first became interested in all this nuclear stuff from reading Carey Sublettes Nuclear Weapons FAQ, and in that FAQ the high-energy-physics section is a must read for folks who want to understand where I'm going.  The GCNR runs at energy levels WAY, WAY beyond any conventional machine, but at levels vastly below the levels used in nuclear weapons design.  <br>
<br>
I personally find it very gratifying to put some of that research and work dedicated to apocalypse into getting the human race out of the cradle.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Finally, I have an ace card I have not even played yet, which is the possibility of using electromagnetics to help a) control the fission vortex and b) keep the reaction chamber cool.  Frankly, I don't think we'll need it, but just keep in mind there are huge areas of extensive research that could be applied to this project that I have not even started using yet. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The limit of Isp for a GCNR with regenitive cooling by the cyrogenic propellant is around 3000s, the higher numbers up to 5-7000s range require external cooling of the whole engine structure in addition to the cryogenic cooling from the fuel. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You would not happen to have any links, would you?  I suspect this is a deep space application, designed to run for long periods of time under low thrust, high Isp conditions.  If you are trying to heat your reaction mass very much hotter than I am, while flowing very little of it, you could see the issues that would arise.  After all, to get 7000 Isp, the exit velocity has to be around 70,000 meters per second, well over twice what the Liberty Ship calls for.  Can't be easy!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Now, very early in this thread the specific heat of hydrogen was discussed, and when I am not quite so sleepy I will try to work out how many joules of cooling 1245 kilos of hydrogen per second could generate.  I suspect it'll be a lot.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I don't see how the booster can lift itself, let alone any payload off the ground.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, until we put some work into building one, we'll never know, will we?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    I have seen (small) nuclear core rockets projected to reach thrust to weight ratios of 35 to 1!   Given my thoughts above, I do not expect a 10 to 1 thrust to weight ratio to be impossible by any stretch, especially given the high thermal gradient of a gas core design.<br>
<br>
Plus, suppose we can only achieve a thrust to weight ratio of 5 to 1.  We have to dedicate an extra 840 thousand pounds to the engines.  Oh no!  Our LEO cargo capacity is barely over a million pounds now!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Figures I have seen range around 100000 lbf for a 56 ton engine. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Post the link then, lets take a look at it!   I post links all the time, lets see yours!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Your Isp also seems high for a nuclear light bulb. Las Alamos did a number of studies on GCNR in the late 1980's and early 1990's and they thought Isp's of between 1600-2000s were possible for a nuclear light bulb, although it might be possible to reach 3000s with major advance. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I happen to think there have been several major advances.  The optical coating and ultra-pure silica are two that permit MUCH higher energy densities with a gaseous core in a lightbulb.  Plus new composites will allow us to enclose large engine volumes for not much mass.  Heck, I bet the heaviest part of these thrusters will be the hydrogen intake plenum, where the three turbopumps will be mounted.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> You havn't answered my question. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Happy now?  Grouch?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
