<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> ALL reaction rockets must follow the inverse relationship between specific power (alpha, represented as @ here) and specific impulse (Isp). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why?  Using well understood high energy design principals, we can drive the power density of a design WAY higher today than we could as recently as three years ago.  How?  Say thanks to Intel and AMD and IBM for all the billions of private research dollars they have sunk into ultraviolet transmissivity.  Thank the guys who just started making 20 cm nanotubes.  Thank the guys who figured out how to make millions of laser drilled micropores in hard metals with super precision.<br>
<br>
Technology moves FAST these days, gotta learn to keep up.  And &quot;speed&quot; is not one of the things I'd expect from a government lab.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
So, in a nutshell, while the inverse relationship of power density to Isp has held in the past, I see no technical reason why we can't smash that trend.<br>
<br>
Of course, I could be wrong.  Heck, yales proved that!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
